slides_data.notes: Say: Hi there! This is a quick byte about Functions with Parameters
☑️ Do This: Define parameter. Reinforce that a parameter only exists inside the function definition.

Ask: What would be the parameter in this example?

Do This: Identify that the parameter is name – the placeholder inside the parentheses when the function is defined on line 1.

☑️ Do This: Define argument.

🎙️ Say: Think of the function like a fill-in-the-blank sentence. The parameter is the blank space, and the argument is the word you choose to put in.

Ask: What is the argument here?

Do this: Identify that "Taylor" is the argument — the actual value being passed into the function. They should understand that the argument replaces the parameter name when the function runs.
☑️ Do This: Explain why parameters are useful for functions.

scenes.speech: Hi there! This is a quick byte about functions with parameters.
scenes.elevenlabs: [warmly welcoming] Hi there! This is a quick byte about functions with parameters.

scenes.speech: So, what exactly is a parameter? A parameter is a placeholder that you put inside your function. Think of it as a blank space waiting for information.
scenes.elevenlabs: [curious] So, what exactly is a parameter? [patiently] A parameter is a placeholder that you put inside your function. [clarifying] Think of it as a blank space waiting for information.

scenes.comment: Identifying the parameter in a code example.
scenes.speech: In this example, 'name' is our parameter. It's the placeholder inside the parentheses when we define our function on line one.
scenes.elevenlabs: [direct] In this example, 'name' is our parameter. [explaining] It's the placeholder inside the parentheses when we define our function on line one.

scenes.speech: Now, what about an argument? An argument is the actual value you give to a function when you use it. You can think of your function like a fill-in-the-blank sentence. The parameter is the blank space, and the argument is the word you choose to put into that blank.
scenes.elevenlabs: [thoughtful] Now, what about an argument? [patiently] An argument is the actual value you give to a function when you use it. [clarifying] You can think of your function like a fill-in-the-blank sentence. The parameter is the blank space, and the argument is the word you choose to put into that blank.

scenes.comment: Identifying the argument in a code example.
scenes.speech: Here, 'Taylor' is the argument. It's the actual value we pass into the function. When the function runs, this argument 'Taylor' replaces the parameter 'name'.
scenes.elevenlabs: [direct] Here, 'Taylor' is the argument. [explaining] It's the actual value we pass into the function. [important] When the function runs, this argument 'Taylor' replaces the parameter 'name'.

scenes.comment: Explaining the benefits of using parameters.
scenes.speech: Why do we use parameters? Well, they let you reuse the same function for many different values without having to write new code each time. This makes your code much easier to update and understand.
scenes.elevenlabs: [enthusiastic] Why do we use parameters? Well, they let you reuse the same function for many different values without having to write new code each time. [emphasized] This makes your code much easier to update and understand.
